00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:52.910
of our Hispanic law collection.

00:00:52.910 --> 00:00:56.330
The Law Library has been collecting
books from foreign jurisdictions

00:00:56.330 --> 00:00:59.010 position:56%
from its very origins in the
beginning of the nineteenth century.

00:00:59.010 --> 00:01:03.690
But the main collecting
activities of legal literature

00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:08.090 position:56%
from foreign jurisdictions didn't
really get underway until the middle

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:09.490
of the nineteenth century.

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:11.240
And the most important event

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:17.480
for that beginning was
the Mexican American War.

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:19.110
The Mexican American War was a war

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:23.060
that took place between
1846 and 1848.

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:26.820
It was a contest especially
over land and at the close

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:30.210
of the war the United States found
itself in possession of New Mexico,

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:37.530
Arizona, California and basically
an entire new continent to the west

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:40.970
of its previous holdings
in North America.

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:46.860
So Congress realizing that that
land until recently had been

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:50.360
under jurisdictions whose
historical roots lie

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:53.610
in the Spanish Empire
realized they would need

00:01:53.610 --> 00:01:57.150
to understand how property
was regulated,

00:01:57.150 --> 00:02:00.120
how contracts were regulated,
how the cities were regulated,

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:01.420
and how the people
understood themselves.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:07.020
So they required the Law Library
of Congress to acquire law books

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:12.970
from those jurisdictions especially
Spain, the Spanish Empire,

00:02:12.970 --> 00:02:14.790
and Mexico until that date.

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:16.820
So that was in 1848.

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:20.600
They didn't actually allocate
funds until 1854 but at

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:24.820
that point the Library went out on
a spending...on a shopping spree

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:30.310 position:56%
and eventually after several decades
of collecting, we have many, many,

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:33.930
many volumes that represent
the entire history of,

00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:37.130
the entire early print
history of Hispanic law

00:02:37.130 --> 00:02:40.610
