00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:53.720
of Hispanic law is shrouded
somewhat in antiquity.

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:57.910
We had at the fall of the Roman
Empire, a small code of Roman law.

00:02:57.910 --> 00:03:00.890
That was the only code of
Roman law that survived

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:04.130
in unbroken tradition
throughout the middle ages.

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:07.610 position:56%
And that was the Breviary of Alaric,
which was a bit of Roman law,

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:11.380
really roman not barbarian
but it was in the hands

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:15.340
of a Germanic tribe,
eventually the Visigothic Tribe

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:18.570
and over centuries it
was adapted and changed

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:23.440
and it becomes the basic,
one of the primary documents

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:27.530
of Hispanic Law, the
Visigothic Code.

00:03:27.530 --> 00:03:30.820
It's published, is printed, for
the first time very late 1550.

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:33.100
We have it here in a 1579 edition.

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:36.230
Already in this edition in
Paris of Sebastian Nevellis,

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:40.180 position:56%
the Visigothic Code was very much an
active law code throughout medieval

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:44.020
Spain and it was eventually folded
into a subsequent publication known

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:47.690
as the Fuero juzgo which remained
living Spanish law throughout

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:51.320
history of the Spanish
Empire in North America.

